{"id":115552,"date":"2025-10-09T14:42:16","date_gmt":"2025-10-09T04:42:16","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/?p=115552"},"modified":"2025-10-09T14:54:59","modified_gmt":"2025-10-09T04:54:59","slug":"anzsco-mismatch-department-instruments-conflict","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/anzsco-mismatch-department-instruments-conflict\/","title":{"rendered":"ANZSCO Mismatch: Department Instruments Conflict"},"content":{"rendered":"[vc_row type=&#8221;in_container&#8221; full_screen_row_position=&#8221;middle&#8221; column_margin=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_tablet=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_phone=&#8221;default&#8221; scene_position=&#8221;center&#8221; text_color=&#8221;dark&#8221; text_align=&#8221;left&#8221; row_border_radius=&#8221;none&#8221; row_border_radius_applies=&#8221;bg&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; overlay_strength=&#8221;0.3&#8243; gradient_direction=&#8221;left_to_right&#8221; shape_divider_position=&#8221;bottom&#8221; bg_image_animation=&#8221;none&#8221;][vc_column column_padding=&#8221;no-extra-padding&#8221; column_padding_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_position=&#8221;all&#8221; column_element_direction_desktop=&#8221;default&#8221; column_element_spacing=&#8221;default&#8221; desktop_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; tablet_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; phone_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; background_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; background_hover_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; column_backdrop_filter=&#8221;none&#8221; column_shadow=&#8221;none&#8221; column_border_radius=&#8221;none&#8221; column_link_target=&#8221;_self&#8221; column_position=&#8221;default&#8221; gradient_direction=&#8221;left_to_right&#8221; overlay_strength=&#8221;0.3&#8243; width=&#8221;1\/1&#8243; tablet_width_inherit=&#8221;default&#8221; animation_type=&#8221;default&#8221; bg_image_animation=&#8221;none&#8221; border_type=&#8221;simple&#8221; column_border_width=&#8221;none&#8221; column_border_style=&#8221;solid&#8221;][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]In late 2024, the Department of Home Affairs quietly <strong>updated five occupations<\/strong> in the <strong>Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List <\/strong>(<a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/www.legislation.gov.au\/F2019L00278\/latest\/text\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">LIN 19\/051: MLTSSL<\/a>) using ANZSCO 2022 titles, despite the law clearly prescribing ANZSCO 2013 for these visas.<\/p>\n<p>The change, made through a legislative instrument, conflicts with the Department\u2019s own legal definition of ANZSCO, leaving these occupations technically incorrect under the Migration Regulations.[\/vc_column_text][vc_row_inner column_margin=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_tablet=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_phone=&#8221;default&#8221; text_align=&#8221;left&#8221; row_position=&#8221;default&#8221; row_position_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; row_position_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; pointer_events=&#8221;all&#8221;][vc_column_inner column_padding=&#8221;padding-3-percent&#8221; column_padding_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_position=&#8221;all&#8221; bottom_margin=&#8221;20&#8243; column_element_direction_desktop=&#8221;default&#8221; column_element_spacing=&#8221;default&#8221; desktop_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; tablet_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; phone_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; background_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; background_hover_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; column_backdrop_filter=&#8221;none&#8221; column_shadow=&#8221;small_depth&#8221; column_border_radius=&#8221;3px&#8221; column_link_target=&#8221;_self&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; gradient_direction=&#8221;left_to_right&#8221; overlay_strength=&#8221;0.3&#8243; width=&#8221;1\/1&#8243; tablet_width_inherit=&#8221;default&#8221; animation_type=&#8221;default&#8221; bg_image_animation=&#8221;none&#8221; border_type=&#8221;simple&#8221; column_border_width=&#8221;none&#8221; column_border_style=&#8221;solid&#8221; column_padding_type=&#8221;default&#8221; gradient_type=&#8221;default&#8221;][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>The Misaligned Five<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\"><strong>ANZSCO Code<\/strong><\/td>\n<td width=\"200\"><strong>ANZSCO v1.2 (2013)<\/strong><\/td>\n<td width=\"200\"><strong>ANZSCO v2022 (2022)<\/strong><\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\">322211<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Sheetmetal Trades Worker<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Sheetmetal Worker<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\">332211<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Painting Trades Worker<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Painter<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\">333211<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Fibrous Plasterer<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Plasterer (Wall and Ceiling)<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\">333212<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Solid Plasterer<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Renderer (Solid Plaster)<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"200\">334113<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Drainer \/ Drainlayer<\/td>\n<td width=\"200\">Drainer<\/td>\n<\/tr>\n<\/tbody>\n<\/table>\n[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>The Issue You Need to Know About<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]On 13 December 2024, the Department registered <a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/www.legislation.gov.au\/F2024L01675\/latest\/text\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>LIN 24\/083<\/em><\/a><em> \u2013 Migration Amendment (Relevant Assessing Authorities and Other Matters) Instrument 2024.<\/em><\/p>\n<p>Among other amendments, it updated <a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/www.legislation.gov.au\/F2019L00278\/latest\/text\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>LIN 19\/051<\/em><\/a><em> \u2013 Specification of Occupations and Assessing Authorities<\/em>, which contains the MLTSSL, <strong>replacing five occupation titles<\/strong> with their <strong>ANZSCO<\/strong> <strong>2022<\/strong> equivalents.<\/p>\n<p>Yet the explanatory statement to <em>LIN 24\/083<\/em> made no mention of these title changes or of any underlying update to the ANZSCO version.<\/p>\n<p>Just a week earlier, on 6 December, the Department had registered <a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/www.legislation.gov.au\/F2024L01616\/asmade\/text\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>LIN 24\/105<\/em><\/a><em> \u2013 Migration (ANZSCO Definition) Specification 2024<\/em>, which defined <strong>ANZSCO v1.2 (2013)<\/strong> as the operative version for all skilled programs under regulation 1.03 \u2014 except for regulations <strong>2.72, 2.73 and 5.19(5)<\/strong> (covering subclasses <strong>482<\/strong> and <strong>186<\/strong>).<\/p>\n<p>In other words, although <em>LIN 24\/105<\/em> had already established <strong>ANZSCO v1.2 (2013)<\/strong> as the governing definition for skilled visas, <em>LIN 24\/083<\/em>\u2014issued only a week later\u2014introduced <strong>ANZSCO 2022 titles<\/strong> into the <strong>MLTSSL<\/strong>. This has created a significant inconsistency between the version of ANZSCO that is legally in force and the titles now displayed in LIN 19\/051 for <strong>GSM visas (189, 190, 491, <\/strong>and<strong> 485).<\/strong>[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>Extent of the Inconsistency<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]The inconsistency is not limited to a single data source; it extends across the Department\u2019s own official sources.<\/p>\n<p>Taking the occupation <strong>332211 \u2013 Painting Trades Worker (v1.2) \/ Painter (v2022)<\/strong> as an example, here\u2019s how it currently appears across official sources for <strong>GSM visas (189, 190, 491, <\/strong>and<strong> 485).<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>SkillSelect<\/strong>: autoloads the occupation as <strong>Painting Trades Worker (v1.2):<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"img-frame alignnone wp-image-116266\" src=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect-300x146.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"291\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect-300x146.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect-1024x497.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect-768x373.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect-1536x745.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/skillselect.jpg 1622w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" \/><\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>Department\u2019s website: <\/strong>displays <strong>Painting Trades Worker (v1.2):<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"img-frame alignnone wp-image-116250\" src=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/DOHA_Website_C.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"589\" height=\"494\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/DOHA_Website_C.png 589w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/DOHA_Website_C-300x252.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 589px) 100vw, 589px\" \/><\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>ImmiAccount (Visa Application System)<\/strong>: autoloads the occupation as Painter (<strong>v2022<\/strong>):<\/p>\n<p><strong><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"img-frame alignnone wp-image-116251 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/ImmiAccount-485.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1513\" height=\"805\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/ImmiAccount-485.png 1513w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/ImmiAccount-485-300x160.png 300w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/ImmiAccount-485-1024x545.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/ImmiAccount-485-768x409.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1513px) 100vw, 1513px\" \/>LIN 19\/051: <\/strong>Within the <em>Medium and Long-term Strategic Skills List (MLTSSL)<\/em>, the occupation appears as <strong>Painter (v2022)<\/strong> \u2014 reflecting the update made through <em>LIN 24\/083<\/em>.<\/p>\n<p><strong><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"img-frame alignnone wp-image-116252 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_MLTSSL_List_C.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"801\" height=\"332\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_MLTSSL_List_C.png 801w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_MLTSSL_List_C-300x124.png 300w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_MLTSSL_List_C-768x318.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 801px) 100vw, 801px\" \/><\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>LIN 19\/051: <\/strong>In the same legislative instrument, the occupation still appears as <strong>Painting Trades Worker (v1.2)<\/strong> in the Assessing Authorities table.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"img-frame alignnone wp-image-116253 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_SkillsAssessment_List_C.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1405\" height=\"460\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_SkillsAssessment_List_C.png 1405w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_SkillsAssessment_List_C-300x98.png 300w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_SkillsAssessment_List_C-1024x335.png 1024w, https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/LIN19-051_SkillsAssessment_List_C-768x251.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1405px) 100vw, 1405px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>This inconsistency is replicated across all five affected occupations.<\/p>\n<p>The Department\u2019s systems and instruments are effectively referencing two different ANZSCO versions for the same roles, depending on where the information is accessed.<\/p>\n<p>Applicants may see the 2022 title (e.g. Painter) in visa application forms, while the legislation that governs eligibility for GSM visas continues to rely on ANZSCO 2013 (e.g. Painting Trades Worker).[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>Why does this matter?<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]This is more than a technical oversight; it represents a legislative misalignment.<\/p>\n<blockquote><p>Under <em>LIN 24\/105<\/em>, ANZSCO 2013 is the prescribed version for all GSM visas. However, by introducing ANZSCO 2022 titles into <em>LIN 19\/051<\/em>, the Department effectively blurred the line between what is legally enforceable and what is operationally displayed.<br \/>\nWhen government systems, instruments, and state agencies start reflecting different ANZSCO versions for the same occupation, it creates <strong>uncertainty<\/strong> and <strong>inconsistency<\/strong>.<\/p><\/blockquote>\n<p>A clear example can be seen in the Queensland State Nomination lists published by <em>Migration Queensland<\/em>.<br \/>\nIn the latest updates:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/migration.qld.gov.au\/occupation-lists\/queensland-onshore-skilled-occupation-list\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Queensland Onshore Skilled Occupation List<\/a> refers to 322211 \u2013 Sheetmetal Worker (the ANZSCO <strong>2022<\/strong> title).<\/li>\n<li>The <a class=\"uline\" href=\"https:\/\/migration.qld.gov.au\/occupation-lists\/offshore-queensland-skilled-occupation-lists-(qsol)\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Queensland Offshore Skilled Occupation List<\/a> refers to 322211 \u2013 Sheetmetal Trades Worker (the ANZSCO <strong>2013<\/strong> title).<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>Both lists refer to the same occupation code, but each uses a title from a different ANZSCO version.[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>Department\u2019s Response<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]Following the identification of this inconsistency, we sought clarification directly from the Department of Home Affairs.<\/p>\n<p>In its official response, the Department confirmed that <em>LIN 24\/105 \u2013 Migration (ANZSCO Definition) Specification 2024<\/em> establishes ANZSCO 2013 as the version defined under regulation 1.03 for all skilled programs, except for regulations 2.72, 2.73, and 5.19(5), which apply to subclasses 482 and 186.<\/p>\n<p>In other words, GSM visas (189, 190, 491, and 485) continue to operate under the ANZSCO 2013 classification, while employer-sponsored visas (482 and 186) utilise the ANZSCO 2022 classification.<\/p>\n<p>The Department also confirmed that there are <strong>no current plans to amend the legislation<\/strong> to align these definitions.[\/vc_column_text][vc_row_inner column_margin=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_tablet=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_phone=&#8221;default&#8221; text_align=&#8221;left&#8221; row_position=&#8221;default&#8221; row_position_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; row_position_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; pointer_events=&#8221;all&#8221;][vc_column_inner column_padding=&#8221;padding-5-percent&#8221; column_padding_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_position=&#8221;all&#8221; column_element_direction_desktop=&#8221;default&#8221; column_element_spacing=&#8221;default&#8221; desktop_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; tablet_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; phone_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; background_color=&#8221;#F3F3F3&#8243; background_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; background_hover_color_opacity=&#8221;1&#8243; column_backdrop_filter=&#8221;none&#8221; column_shadow=&#8221;none&#8221; column_border_radius=&#8221;none&#8221; column_link_target=&#8221;_self&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; gradient_direction=&#8221;left_to_right&#8221; overlay_strength=&#8221;0.3&#8243; width=&#8221;1\/1&#8243; tablet_width_inherit=&#8221;default&#8221; animation_type=&#8221;default&#8221; bg_image_animation=&#8221;none&#8221; border_type=&#8221;simple&#8221; column_border_width=&#8221;none&#8221; column_border_style=&#8221;solid&#8221; column_padding_type=&#8221;default&#8221; gradient_type=&#8221;default&#8221;][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]\n<h2>Our Analysis<\/h2>\n[\/vc_column_text][vc_column_text css=&#8221;&#8221; text_direction=&#8221;default&#8221;]While the legislative inconsistency is now confirmed, the underlying cause appears to be technical rather than intentional.<\/p>\n<p>In our view, the issue likely stems from the coexistence of two distinct ANZSCO data frameworks \u2014 version 1.2 (2013) and version 2022 \u2014 being used simultaneously across different visa programs.<\/p>\n<p>Each version represents an independent catalogue with separate occupational datasets, and integrating both within the same system introduces inevitable complexity and inconsistency.<\/p>\n<p>When the Department introduced ANZSCO 2022 for subclasses 482 and 186, this likely created compatibility challenges in the software platforms and databases that power SkillSelect, ImmiAccount, and the legislative occupation tables.<\/p>\n<p>While this is, of course, our humble interpretation, it highlights the broader difficulty of maintaining legislative and technical consistency when two classification systems must coexist within the same regulatory framework.[\/vc_column_text][\/vc_column_inner][\/vc_row_inner][divider line_type=&#8221;Small Line&#8221; line_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; line_thickness=&#8221;1&#8243; divider_color=&#8221;default&#8221; custom_height=&#8221;100&#8243;][nectar_global_section id=&#8221;109891&#8243;][\/vc_column][\/vc_row]\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>[vc_row type=&#8221;in_container&#8221; full_screen_row_position=&#8221;middle&#8221; column_margin=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_tablet=&#8221;default&#8221; column_direction_phone=&#8221;default&#8221; scene_position=&#8221;center&#8221; text_color=&#8221;dark&#8221; text_align=&#8221;left&#8221; row_border_radius=&#8221;none&#8221; row_border_radius_applies=&#8221;bg&#8221; overflow=&#8221;visible&#8221; overlay_strength=&#8221;0.3&#8243; gradient_direction=&#8221;left_to_right&#8221; shape_divider_position=&#8221;bottom&#8221; bg_image_animation=&#8221;none&#8221;][vc_column column_padding=&#8221;no-extra-padding&#8221; column_padding_tablet=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_phone=&#8221;inherit&#8221; column_padding_position=&#8221;all&#8221; column_element_direction_desktop=&#8221;default&#8221; column_element_spacing=&#8221;default&#8221; desktop_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221; tablet_text_alignment=&#8221;default&#8221;&#8230;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":115555,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"_acf_changed":false,"footnotes":""},"categories":[140,118,90,129],"tags":[],"class_list":{"0":"post-115552","1":"post","2":"type-post","3":"status-publish","4":"format-standard","5":"has-post-thumbnail","7":"category-anzsco","8":"category-migration-program","9":"category-occupation-list","10":"category-skilled-visa"},"acf":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/115552","targetHints":{"allow":["GET"]}}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=115552"}],"version-history":[{"count":5,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/115552\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":116275,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/115552\/revisions\/116275"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/115555"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=115552"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=115552"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.anzscosearch.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=115552"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}